entry.title: Add ScopedGSignal for managing GLib signal lifetime
entry.content:
Currently, g_signal_connect() is used in //remoting, //ui/gtk,

//net //third_party/webrtc, and //content/browser/accessibility.

In almost all cases, the signal isn't disconnected when receiving

objects are destroyed, which can lead to use-after-frees.



This CL adds ScopedGSignal for safer management of GLib signal

lifetime since proper management of GLib signals is surprisingly

tricky: g_signal_handler_disconnect() should be called when the

signal is no longer needed, but if the sender is deallocated

before disconnecting, a crash will occur in GLib. Therefore we

also need to listen for sender destruction. However, this

creates some more problems since GLib may run the destruction

callback asynchronously after we've disconnected from the signal,

so we also need to carefully remove the destruction callback

in the appropriate places.



Followup CLs will convert usages of g_signal_connect() to

ScopedGSignal, and a presubmit check will be added to prevent

new usages of g_signal_connect().

entry.title: Clarify CreateRequestHandler responsibility
entry.content:
This CL clarifies that



- `CreateRequestHandler()` is responsible for final checks

for servability, rather than `GetServableState()`.

- Its caller (`PrefetchURLLoaderInterceptor` and

`PrefetchService`) is responsible for cookie-related

checks.



This CL changes the contract of `CreateRequestHandler()`

so that it can return null and thus adds a null handler check

in PrefetchURLLoaderInterceptor (the only non-test caller of

`CreateRequestHandler()`), but at the time of this CL

`CreateRequestHandler()` doesn't return null handler yet.



Subsequent CLs e.g.

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4893246

will actually make `CreateRequestHandler()` return null handler.

entry.title: Avoid late-processing of display suspend during resume
entry.content:
When ARCVM resumes, the first thing it does is process a

SetInteractive(false), which got interrupted a long time ago,

in the middle of suspending.

This is unnecessary (sleep while trying to wake up) and it

causes instability.



This CL eliminates this issue by ignoring display-power-down

requests issued in the middle of the suspend process.



BUG=b:302041823

TEST=manual lid close/open with '--vmodule=arc_power_bridge=1'

in /etc/chrome_dev.conf , with/without doze, plus

Unit Tests.

entry.title: Revert "Switch 'Android arm Builder (dbg)' to a component build"
entry.content:
This reverts commit f502f8cb562a6f2f1e768b1bb63382e7d1f34ce3.



Reason for revert: turns out some junit suites don't like running

on component builds

eg: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Android%20arm%20Builder%20(dbg)/73026/overview



Will drop this back down to static builds. Builds directly before

this CL were actually green, so many changing things aren't

needed. But if they are, will look into changing machine specs

instead.



Original change's description:

> Switch 'Android arm Builder (dbg)' to a component build

>

> https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/android-archive-dbg

> https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Android%20arm%20Builder%20%28dbg%29

>

> In https://crrev.com/c/4875696, the former builder was replaced with

> the latter build, and the latter builder switched to compiling 'all'

> to match coverage.

>

> However, since being replaced, the latter builder is now failing its

> builds mysteriously. This is likely due to OOMs. The former builder

> likely avoided these issues since it was a component build and did not

> have to link giant static binaries in one-go. So this changes the latter

> builder to match and hopefully avoid the OOMs.

>

> Note that this builder doesn't trigger any child builders/testers. So

> it won't adversely affect any test coverage.

entry.content:

setting is retained after navigations that didn't use to change

change RFHs on those navigations, by using a SiteInstance -> setting

map instead.

entry.title: Parse JSON on Android just like other platforms
entry.content:
Android's strategy for parsing untrusted JSON has been to "sanitize" the

JSON by round-tripping it through a Java (memory-safe) parser, and then

parsing it with the in-process JSON parser. This is to avoid spawning a

service process as is done on other platforms.



With the advent of the Rust parser, controlled both by build and runtime

flags, we want to use that on Android when enabled.



This refactors the #ifdef's to be more intelligible and avoid

duplicating code.

entry.title: Fix showing of web contents dialogs
entry.content:
When showing a web contents dialog while the web contents is in the

"occluded" state and the user subsequently makes the web contents

visible, WebContentsModalDialogManager won't show the dialog. This is

problematic for dialogs which block the main thread of the renderer

process, because the page becomes completely unresponsive and there is

no way for the user to make it interactive again because the dialog

isn't showing.



This patch fixes this by checking to see if the dialog is active during

the transition from "occluded" to "visible", and showing it if it isn't

active.

necessary, and we could do with regular toasts that are not anchored to
